## Use `System.IO.Abstractions`

This is a battle-tested NuGet package that wraps all file system statics behind mockable interfaces — no need to write custom wrappers.

### 1. Install

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject into your classes

```csharp
public class MyService(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Read(string path) => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Write(string path, string content) => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool EnsureDir(string path) => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

// Directory.Exists works too — /data/ is implicitly created
var svc = new MyService(mockFs);
Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", svc.Read("/data/config.json"));
```

### Migration steps

1. Add the NuGet package
2. Replace `File.*` / `Directory.*` calls with `fileSystem.File.*` / `fileSystem.Directory.*`
3. Add `IFileSystem` as a constructor parameter (DI handles the rest)

This covers `ReadAllText`, `WriteAllText`, and `Directory.Exists` in one abstraction. No custom interfaces needed.
